    <text id="A3057T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>McCutchan tells Miller that he has not written because he hoped for news from
                    home, and he asks for more money.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Mrs. A.V.L. Miller<lb/>York Pa</name>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1864-12-19"><abbr expan="December">Dec </abbr>19th 1864</date>
                        <name type="place">Fort Delaware</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Mrs Miller</salute>
                </opener>

                <p> Your letter to me was detained several weeks and I defered an answer hoping to
                    hear from your friends in Augusta but there has been no flag of truce since I am
                    not permitted to receive such things as you <unclear>propose</unclear> to send
                    except from a near relative I am only allowed to receive money from friends and
                    can purchase the small articles if you will be good enough to send me a few
                    dollars of greenback Enclosed one Confederate postage stamp for you to write to
                    your friend in Virignia.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>My respects to all your family and believe me as ever your sincere
                        friend</salute>
                    <signed>Jas. Y. McCutchan</signed>
                    <seg type="postscript">I have written home in regard to your welfare</seg>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
